{
  "doc_id": "60454",
  "text": "Since the late 1990s an increasing number of epidemiological studies have analysed whether the socioeconomic, built, social or ethnic neighbourhood environment have an independent effect on individual health outcomes or health-related behaviours [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . There is an overall conclusion that underlying mechanisms of the association between neighbourhood environments and health are quite complex and both mediating and interacting mechanisms should be considered. Therefore, various conceptual models were developed describing pathways explaining associations between neighbourhood context and individual health [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] .",
